</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="19C96549FF906C5DF99638FF1E93FE1E" lastPageId="29" lastPageNumber="30" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="516C36C2FF906C5CF99638FF1ECFFB96" blockId="28.[151,1437,691,2014]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">
<emphasis id="63A7EAD0FF906C5CF99638FF1C66FD1A" bold="true" box="[199,332,727,753]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Discussion.</emphasis>
Transfer of most taxa traditionally assigned to 
<taxonomicName id="96D34D41FF906C5CFA0A38FF1930FD1A" authorityName="Opik" authorityYear="1937" box="[859,1050,727,753]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Sphaerexochinae">Sphaerexochinae</taxonomicName>
to Acanthoparyphinae and restriction of 
<taxonomicName id="96D34D41FF906C5CF9B938D31C8DFCFE" authorityName="Opik" authorityYear="1937" box="[232,423,763,789]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Sphaerexochinae">Sphaerexochinae</taxonomicName>
to 
<taxonomicName id="96D34D41FF906C5CF89B38D31F58FCFE" authorityName="Beyrich" authorityYear="1845" box="[458,626,763,789]" class="Trilobita" family="Cheiruridae" genus="Sphaerexochus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phacopida" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="63A7EAD0FF906C5CF89B38D31F58FCFE" box="[458,626,763,789]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Sphaerexochus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
itself were discussed above. To reiterate, 
<taxonomicName id="96D34D41FF906C5CFD1438D319C7FCFE" authorityName="Beyrich" authorityYear="1845" box="[1093,1261,763,789]" class="Trilobita" family="Cheiruridae" genus="Sphaerexochus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phacopida" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="63A7EAD0FF906C5CFD1438D319C7FCFE" box="[1093,1261,763,789]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Sphaerexochus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a morphology of a ten segment thorax, highly tagmatized pygidium, and robust thoracic segments that is unique in 
<taxonomicName id="96D34D41FF906C5CFC49393718B6FCD2" authorityName="Hawle and Corda" authorityYear="1847" box="[1304,1436,799,825]" class="Trilobita" family="Cheiruridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phacopida" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Cheiruridae</taxonomicName>
and its affinities within the family are difficult to determine. The oldest known species that has been assigned is the Floian 
<taxonomicName id="96D34D41FF906C5CF840394F1F73FC6A" authority="Cugaeva, 1973" authorityName="Cugaeva" authorityYear="1973" box="[273,601,871,900]" class="Trilobita" family="Cheiruridae" genus="Sphaerexochus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phacopida" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="trisulcatus">
<emphasis id="63A7EAD0FF906C5CF840394F1C8FFC6A" box="[273,421,871,897]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">S. trisulcatus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="35424B33FF906C5CF8FC39411F73FC6A" author="Cugaeva, M. N." box="[429,601,871,900]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" pagination="43 - 122" refId="ref35846" refString="Cugaeva, M. N. (1973) [Trilobites]. In: Cugaeva, M. N., Ivanova, V. A., Oradovskaya, M. N. &amp; Yakovlev, U. N. (Eds.), [Bios- tratigraphy of the lower part of the Ordovician in the North-east of the USSR, and biogeography of the uppermost Lower Ordovician]. Trudy Geologicheskogo Instituta. Akademiya Nauk SSSR, 213, 43 - 122. [in Russian]" type="journal article" year="1973">Čugaeva, 1973</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, from the Khiti Formation, 
<collectingRegion id="9317F820FF906C5CFAC4394F197BFC6A" box="[917,1105,871,897]" country="Russia" name="Magadan" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Magadan Oblast</collectingRegion>
, far eastern 
<collectingCountry id="29C47652FF906C5CFD8D394F180DFC6A" box="[1244,1319,871,897]" name="Russia" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Russia</collectingCountry>
(Kolyma- Omolon Terrane). This species is known only from three incomplete cranidia. While it is not inconceivable that they could represent a species of 
<taxonomicName id="96D34D41FF906C5CF8B039871FA3FC22" authorityName="Beyrich" authorityYear="1845" box="[481,649,943,969]" class="Trilobita" family="Cheiruridae" genus="Sphaerexochus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phacopida" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="63A7EAD0FF906C5CF8B039871FA3FC22" box="[481,649,943,969]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Sphaerexochus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, they could also represent an acanthoparyphine. Without knowledge of the librigena and particularly the pygidium, it is difficult to accept an assignment to the genus, particularly as it would involve a substantial stratigraphic range extension. No other Floian species and no Dapingian species have been assigned. The oldest definite species are Darriwilian and are from the Laurentian-affinity Midland Valley Terrane, 
<collectingCountry id="29C47652FF906C5CF9863E171C13FBB2" box="[215,313,1087,1113]" name="United Kingdom" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Scotland</collectingCountry>
(
<taxonomicName id="96D34D41FF906C5CF81A3E171F1FFBB2" authority="Tripp, 1962" authorityName="Tripp" authorityYear="1962" box="[331,565,1087,1113]" class="Trilobita" family="Cheiruridae" genus="Sphaerexochus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phacopida" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="eurys">
<emphasis id="63A7EAD0FF906C5CF81A3E171C8CFBB2" box="[331,422,1087,1113]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">S. eurys</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="35424B33FF906C5CF8FC3E171F1FFBB2" author="Tripp, R. P." box="[429,565,1087,1113]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" pagination="1 - 40" refId="ref38757" refString="Tripp, R. P. (1962) Trilobites from the &quot; confinis &quot; Flags (Ordovician) of the Girvan district, Ayrshire. Transactions of the Royal Society of Edinburgh, 65, 1 - 40. https: // doi. org / 10.1017 / S 0080456800012291" type="journal article" year="1962">Tripp, 1962</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
; 
<taxonomicName id="96D34D41FF906C5CFB123E171E03FBB1" authority="Tripp, 1967" authorityName="Tripp" authorityYear="1967" box="[579,809,1087,1114]" class="Trilobita" family="Cheiruridae" genus="Sphaerexochus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phacopida" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="filius">
<emphasis id="63A7EAD0FF906C5CFB123E171FB2FBB2" box="[579,664,1087,1113]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">S. filius</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="35424B33FF906C5CFBF03E171E03FBB1" author="Tripp, R. P." box="[673,809,1087,1114]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" pagination="43 - 94" refId="ref38808" refString="Tripp, R. P. (1967) Trilobites from the upper Stinchar Limestone (Ordovician) of the Girvan District, Ayrshire. Transactions of the Royal Society of Edinburgh, 67, 43 - 94. https: // doi. org / 10.1017 / S 0080456800023899" type="journal article" year="1967">Tripp, 1967</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
). These species already have the fully derived pygidial morphology typical of the genus and provide no obvious clue to its affinity.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="516C36C2FF906C5CF9963EAF1EE8F971" blockId="28.[151,1437,691,2014]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">
Apart from 
<taxonomicName id="96D34D41FF906C5CF81A3EAF1CD9FB4A" authorityName="Beyrich" authorityYear="1845" box="[331,499,1159,1185]" class="Trilobita" family="Cheiruridae" genus="Sphaerexochus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phacopida" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="63A7EAD0FF906C5CF81A3EAF1CD9FB4A" box="[331,499,1159,1185]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Sphaerexochus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
itself and the taxa transferred above to Acanthoparyphinae, the other group that has often been classified as 
<taxonomicName id="96D34D41FF906C5CF8F03E831F4AFB2E" authorityName="Opik" authorityYear="1937" box="[417,608,1195,1221]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Sphaerexochinae">Sphaerexochinae</taxonomicName>
is a small but highly distinctive clade including 
<taxonomicName id="96D34D41FF906C5CFD2D3E8319DEFB2E" authorityName="Raymond" authorityYear="1905" box="[1148,1268,1195,1221]" class="Trilobita" family="Cheiruridae" genus="Heliomera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phacopida" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="63A7EAD0FF906C5CFD2D3E8319DEFB2E" box="[1148,1268,1195,1221]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Heliomera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="96D34D41FF906C5CFC7B3E831DF8FB02" authorityName="Evitt" authorityYear="1951" class="Trilobita" family="Cheiruridae" genus="Heliomeroides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phacopida" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="63A7EAD0FF906C5CFC7B3E831DF8FB02" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Heliomeroides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. These taxa have had a history of taxonomic flux, with opinion varying on whether they are distinct genera (e.g., 
<bibRefCitation id="35424B33FF906C5CF9893EDB1C49FAE6" author="Evitt, W. R." box="[216,355,1266,1293]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" pagination="587 - 616" refId="ref36272" refString="Evitt, W. R. (1951) Some Middle Ordovician trilobites of the families Cheiruridae, Harpidae and Lichidae. Journal of Paleontology, 25, 587 - 616." type="journal article" year="1951">Evitt [1951]</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="35424B33FF906C5CF8213EDB1F29FAE6" author="Shaw, F. C." box="[368,515,1266,1293]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" pagination="1 - 163" refId="ref38410" refString="Shaw, F. C. (1968) Early Middle Ordovician Chazy trilobites of New York. New York State Museum and Science Service Memoir, 17, 1 - 163." type="journal article" year="1968">Shaw [1968]</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="35424B33FF906C5CFB413EDB1EA0FAE6" author="Chatterton, B. D. E. &amp; Ludvigsen, R." box="[528,906,1266,1293]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" pagination="1 - 106" refId="ref35563" refString="Chatterton, B. D. E. &amp; Ludvigsen, R. (1976) Silicified Middle Ordovician trilobites from the South Nahanni River area, District of Mackenzie, Canada. Palaeontographica, Abteilung A, 154, 1 - 106." type="journal article" year="1976">Chatterton and Ludvigsen [1976]</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="35424B33FF906C5CFAC73EDB199AFAE6" author="Edgecombe, G. D. &amp; Chatterton, B. D. E. &amp; Vaccari, N. E. &amp; Waisfeld, B. G." box="[918,1200,1266,1294]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" pagination="1155 - 1175" refId="ref36074" refString="Edgecombe, G. D., Chatterton, B. D. E., Vaccari, N. E. &amp; Waisfeld, B. G. (1999) Ordovician cheirurid trilobites from the Argentine Precordillera. Journal of Paleontology, 73, 1155 - 1175. https: // doi. org / 10.1017 / S 0022336000031048" type="journal article" year="1999">
Edgecombe 
<emphasis id="63A7EAD0FF906C5CFD723EDC197FFAE6" box="[1059,1109,1267,1293]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">et al</emphasis>
. [1999]
</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="35424B33FF906C5CFDEC3EDB18A5FAE6" author="Zhou, Z. - Y. &amp; Zhou, Z. - Q. &amp; Yin, G. - Z." box="[1213,1423,1266,1294]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" pagination="289 - 328" refId="ref39744" refString="Zhou, Z. - Y., Zhou, Z. - Q. &amp; Yin, G. - Z. (2016) Ordovician trilobites from the uppermost Zhuozishan Formation (early Darriwilian) at Zhuozishan, Wuhai, Inner Mongolia. Memoirs of the Association of Australasian Palaeontologists, 49, 289 - 328." type="journal article" year="2016">
Zhou 
<emphasis id="63A7EAD0FF906C5CFC513EDC1818FAE6" box="[1280,1330,1267,1293]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">et al</emphasis>
. [2016]
</bibRefCitation>
), whether 
<taxonomicName id="96D34D41FF906C5CF9AD3F3F1C8AFADA" authorityName="Evitt" authorityYear="1951" box="[252,416,1303,1329]" class="Trilobita" family="Cheiruridae" genus="Heliomeroides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phacopida" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="63A7EAD0FF906C5CF9AD3F3F1C8AFADA" box="[252,416,1303,1329]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Heliomeroides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
should be considered a subgenus of 
<taxonomicName id="96D34D41FF906C5CFA023F3F1EE1FADA" authorityName="Raymond" authorityYear="1905" box="[851,971,1303,1329]" class="Trilobita" family="Cheiruridae" genus="Heliomera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phacopida" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="63A7EAD0FF906C5CFA023F3F1EE1FADA" box="[851,971,1303,1329]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Heliomera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(e.g., 
<bibRefCitation id="35424B33FF906C5CFD463F3F19DCFADA" author="Whittington, H. B." box="[1047,1270,1302,1329]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" pagination="275 - 442" refId="ref39239" refString="Whittington, H. B. (1965) Trilobites of the Ordovician Table Head Formation, western Newfoundland. Bulletin of the Museum of Comparative Zoology, Harvard, 132, 275 - 442." type="journal article" year="1965">Whittington [1965]</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="35424B33FF906C5CFC543F3018BDFADA" author="Dean, W. T." box="[1285,1431,1302,1330]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" pagination="1 - 60" refId="ref36034" refString="Dean, W. T. (1971) The trilobites of the Chair of Kildare Limestone (upper Ordovician) of eastern Ireland. Part 1. Monographs of the Palaeontographical Society, 531, 1 - 60." type="journal article" year="1971">Dean [1971]</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="35424B33FF906C5CF9C63F131C90FABE" author="Morris, S. F. &amp; Fortey, R. A." box="[151,442,1338,1366]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" refId="ref37539" refString="Morris, S. F. &amp; Fortey, R. A. (1985) Catalogue of the type and figured specimens of trilobites in the British Museum (Natural History). British Museum (Natural History), London, 183 pp." type="book" year="1985">Morris and Fortey [1985]</bibRefCitation>
, Přibyl and Vaněk in 
<bibRefCitation id="35424B33FF906C5CFBFE3F131EA0FABE" author="Pribyl, A. &amp; Vanek, J. &amp; Pek, I." box="[687,906,1338,1366]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" pagination="107 - 193" refId="ref37937" refString="Pribyl, A., Vanek, J. &amp; Pek, I. (1985) Phylogeny and taxonomy of family Cheiruridae (Trilobita). Acta Universitatis Palackianae Olomucensis Facultas rerum naturalium, 83, 107 - 193." type="journal article" year="1985">
Přibyl 
<emphasis id="63A7EAD0FF906C5CFBAD3F141E04FABE" box="[764,814,1339,1365]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">et al</emphasis>
. [1985]
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="35424B33FF906C5CFAC63F14194BFABE" author="Hammann, W." box="[919,1121,1338,1366]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" pagination="3 - 219" refId="ref36445" refString="Hammann, W. (1992) The Ordovician trilobites from the Iberian Chains in the province of Aragon, NE-Spain. I. The trilobites of the Cystoid Limestone (Ashgill Series). Beringeria, 6, 3 - 219." type="journal article" year="1992">Hammann [1992]</bibRefCitation>
), or whether 
<taxonomicName id="96D34D41FF906C5CFDA93F1318B6FABE" authorityName="Evitt" authorityYear="1951" box="[1272,1436,1339,1365]" class="Trilobita" family="Cheiruridae" genus="Heliomeroides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phacopida" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="63A7EAD0FF906C5CFDA93F1318B6FABE" box="[1272,1436,1339,1365]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Heliomeroides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
should be considered a junior subjective synonym of 
<taxonomicName id="96D34D41FF906C5CFBB83F771E4BFA92" authorityName="Raymond" authorityYear="1905" box="[745,865,1375,1401]" class="Trilobita" family="Cheiruridae" genus="Heliomera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phacopida" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="63A7EAD0FF906C5CFBB83F771E4BFA92" box="[745,865,1375,1401]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Heliomera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(e.g., 
<bibRefCitation id="35424B33FF906C5CFAF63F77191DFA92" author="Tripp, R. P." box="[935,1079,1374,1401]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" pagination="43 - 94" refId="ref38808" refString="Tripp, R. P. (1967) Trilobites from the upper Stinchar Limestone (Ordovician) of the Girvan District, Ayrshire. Transactions of the Royal Society of Edinburgh, 67, 43 - 94. https: // doi. org / 10.1017 / S 0080456800023899" type="journal article" year="1967">Tripp [1967]</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="35424B33FF906C5CFD123F4819E5FA92" author="Lane, P. D." box="[1091,1231,1374,1402]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" pagination="1 - 95" refId="ref36961" refString="Lane, P. D. (1971) British Cheiruridae (Trilobita). Monographs of the Palaeontographical Society, 530, 1 - 95." type="journal article" year="1971">Lane [1971]</bibRefCitation>
). The genera were assigned to a new Subfamily 
<taxonomicName id="96D34D41FF906C5CF8B83FAB1FABFA76" box="[489,641,1411,1437]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Heliomerinae">Heliomerinae</taxonomicName>
by 
<bibRefCitation id="35424B33FF906C5CFBFE3FAB1E16FA75" author="Evitt, W. R." box="[687,828,1411,1438]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" pagination="587 - 616" refId="ref36272" refString="Evitt, W. R. (1951) Some Middle Ordovician trilobites of the families Cheiruridae, Harpidae and Lichidae. Journal of Paleontology, 25, 587 - 616." type="journal article" year="1951">Evitt (1951)</bibRefCitation>
, and this was followed by Whittington (1963) before he later (
<bibRefCitation id="35424B33FF906C5CF9AF3F8F1CE4FA29" author="Whittington, H. B." box="[254,462,1447,1474]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" pagination="275 - 442" refId="ref39239" refString="Whittington, H. B. (1965) Trilobites of the Ordovician Table Head Formation, western Newfoundland. Bulletin of the Museum of Comparative Zoology, Harvard, 132, 275 - 442." type="journal article" year="1965">Whittington, 1965</bibRefCitation>
) transferred 
<taxonomicName id="96D34D41FF906C5CFB333F8F1FF0FA2A" authorityName="Raymond" authorityYear="1905" box="[610,730,1447,1473]" class="Trilobita" family="Cheiruridae" genus="Heliomera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phacopida" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="63A7EAD0FF906C5CFB333F8F1FF0FA2A" box="[610,730,1447,1473]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Heliomera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
to 
<taxonomicName id="96D34D41FF906C5CFA503F8F1EEEFA2A" authorityName="Opik" authorityYear="1937" box="[769,964,1447,1473]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Sphaerexochinae">Sphaerexochinae</taxonomicName>
. Since then, some workers have assigned them to 
<taxonomicName id="96D34D41FF906C5CF9A73FE31C9FFA0E" authorityName="Opik" authorityYear="1937" box="[246,437,1483,1509]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Sphaerexochinae">Sphaerexochinae</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation id="35424B33FF906C5CF8943FE31F63FA0E" author="Lane, P. D." box="[453,585,1483,1509]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" pagination="1 - 95" refId="ref36961" refString="Lane, P. D. (1971) British Cheiruridae (Trilobita). Monographs of the Palaeontographical Society, 530, 1 - 95." type="journal article" year="1971">Lane, 1971</bibRefCitation>
; Přibyl and Vaněk in 
<bibRefCitation id="35424B33FF906C5CFA113FE3193AFA0D" author="Pribyl, A. &amp; Vanek, J. &amp; Pek, I." box="[832,1040,1483,1510]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" pagination="107 - 193" refId="ref37937" refString="Pribyl, A., Vanek, J. &amp; Pek, I. (1985) Phylogeny and taxonomy of family Cheiruridae (Trilobita). Acta Universitatis Palackianae Olomucensis Facultas rerum naturalium, 83, 107 - 193." type="journal article" year="1985">
Přibyl 
<emphasis id="63A7EAD0FF906C5CFADD3FE41E95FA0E" box="[908,959,1483,1509]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">et al</emphasis>
., 1985
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="35424B33FF906C5CFD4C3FE31804FA0E" author="Edgecombe, G. D. &amp; Chatterton, B. D. E. &amp; Vaccari, N. E. &amp; Waisfeld, B. G." box="[1053,1326,1483,1510]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" pagination="1155 - 1175" refId="ref36074" refString="Edgecombe, G. D., Chatterton, B. D. E., Vaccari, N. E. &amp; Waisfeld, B. G. (1999) Ordovician cheirurid trilobites from the Argentine Precordillera. Journal of Paleontology, 73, 1155 - 1175. https: // doi. org / 10.1017 / S 0022336000031048" type="journal article" year="1999">
Edgecombe 
<emphasis id="63A7EAD0FF906C5CFDFB3FE419F6FA0E" box="[1194,1244,1483,1509]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">et al</emphasis>
., 1999
</bibRefCitation>
), some to 
<taxonomicName id="96D34D41FF906C5CF9C63FC71C05F9E2" box="[151,303,1519,1545]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Heliomerinae">Heliomerinae</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation id="35424B33FF906C5CF86F3FC71CEFF9E2" author="Shaw, F. C." box="[318,453,1519,1545]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" pagination="1 - 163" refId="ref38410" refString="Shaw, F. C. (1968) Early Middle Ordovician Chazy trilobites of New York. New York State Museum and Science Service Memoir, 17, 1 - 163." type="journal article" year="1968">Shaw, 1968</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="35424B33FF906C5CF8813FC71F4CF9E2" author="Adrain, J. M." box="[464,614,1519,1545]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" pagination="698 - 718" refId="ref34853" refString="Adrain, J. M. (1998) Systematics of the Acanthoparyphinae (Trilobita), with species from the Silurian of Arctic Canada. Journal of Paleontology, 72, 698 - 718. https: // doi. org / 10.1017 / S 0022336000040403" type="journal article" year="1998">Adrain, 1998</bibRefCitation>
), and some, following the arguments of 
<bibRefCitation id="35424B33FF906C5CFD7B3FC718B2F9E2" author="Chatterton, B. D. E. &amp; Ludvigsen, R." box="[1066,1432,1519,1545]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" pagination="1 - 106" refId="ref35563" refString="Chatterton, B. D. E. &amp; Ludvigsen, R. (1976) Silicified Middle Ordovician trilobites from the South Nahanni River area, District of Mackenzie, Canada. Palaeontographica, Abteilung A, 154, 1 - 106." type="journal article" year="1976">Chatterton and Ludvigsen (1976</bibRefCitation>
, p. 65) to Acanthoparyphinae (
<bibRefCitation id="35424B33FF906C5CF8B03C3B1F8BF9C6" author="Ludvigsen, R." box="[481,673,1555,1581]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" pagination="1 - 99" refId="ref37309" refString="Ludvigsen, R. (1979) A trilobite zonation of Middle Ordovician rocks, southwestern District of Mackenzie. Geological Survey of Canada Bulletin, 312, 1 - 99." type="journal article" year="1979">Ludvigsen, 1979</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="35424B33FF906C5CFBFD3C3B1E40F9C6" author="Chatterton, B. D. E." box="[684,874,1555,1581]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" pagination="1 - 74" refId="ref35525" refString="Chatterton, B. D. E. (1980) Ontogenetic studies of Middle Ordovician trilobites from the Esbataottine Formation, Mackenzie Mountains, Canada. Palaeontographica, Abteilung A, 171, 1 - 74." type="journal article" year="1980">Chatterton, 1980</bibRefCitation>
; Ingham 
<emphasis id="63A7EAD0FF906C5CFA803C3C1ECDF9C6" box="[977,999,1556,1581]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">in</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="35424B33FF906C5CFABC3C3B19EDF9C6" author="Ingham, J. K. &amp; Curry, G. B. &amp; Williams, A." box="[1005,1223,1555,1582]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" pagination="481 - 513" refId="ref36690" refString="Ingham, J. K., Curry, G. B. &amp; Williams, A. (1986) Early Ordovician Dounans Limestone fauna, Highland Border Complex, Scotland. Transactions of the Royal Society of Edinburgh: Earth Sciences, 76, 481 - 513. [for 1985]" type="journal article" year="1986">
Ingham 
<emphasis id="63A7EAD0FF906C5CFD193C3C1952F9C6" box="[1096,1144,1555,1581]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">et al</emphasis>
., 1986
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="35424B33FF906C5CFD833C3C18BAF9C6" author="Hammann, W." box="[1234,1424,1555,1582]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" pagination="3 - 219" refId="ref36445" refString="Hammann, W. (1992) The Ordovician trilobites from the Iberian Chains in the province of Aragon, NE-Spain. I. The trilobites of the Cystoid Limestone (Ashgill Series). Beringeria, 6, 3 - 219." type="journal article" year="1992">Hammann, 1992</bibRefCitation>
). Work is in progress on description of new genera and species of the group and consideration of its affinity. For the time being we treat its members as comprising a small Subfamily 
<taxonomicName id="96D34D41FF906C5CFA2D3C731932F99E" box="[892,1048,1627,1653]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Heliomerinae">Heliomerinae</taxonomicName>
. There are no compelling morphological reasons to suppose it is phylogenetically close to 
<taxonomicName id="96D34D41FF906C5CFA433C571E90F972" authorityName="Beyrich" authorityYear="1845" box="[786,954,1663,1689]" class="Trilobita" family="Cheiruridae" genus="Sphaerexochus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phacopida" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="63A7EAD0FF906C5CFA433C571E90F972" box="[786,954,1663,1689]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Sphaerexochus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="516C36C2FF906C5DF9963C8B1EA3FF3E" blockId="28.[151,1437,691,2014]" lastBlockId="29.[151,1437,151,501]" lastPageId="29" lastPageNumber="30" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">
<taxonomicName id="96D34D41FF906C5CF9963C8B1C45F956" authorityName="Beyrich" authorityYear="1845" box="[199,367,1699,1725]" class="Trilobita" family="Cheiruridae" genus="Sphaerexochus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phacopida" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="63A7EAD0FF906C5CF9963C8B1C45F956" box="[199,367,1699,1725]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Sphaerexochus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a sprawling genus, with 50 formally named species currently accepted (along with four currently considered junior subjective synonyms) and at least 16 further reports of species in open nomenclature. This compares with Acanthoparyphinae (as understood herein) with a total of 112 formally named and accepted species, which are currently classified in 13 separate genera. 
<bibRefCitation id="35424B33FF906C5CFBB73D27196EF8C1" author="Kobayashi, T. &amp; Hamada, T." box="[742,1092,1807,1834]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" pagination="367 - 370" refId="ref36824" refString="Kobayashi, T. &amp; Hamada, T. (1976) A new Silurian trilobite from Ofunato, North Japan. Proceedings of the Japan Academy, 52, 367 - 370." type="journal article" year="1976">Kobayashi and Hamada (1976)</bibRefCitation>
proposed a subgenus, 
<taxonomicName id="96D34D41FF906C5CFC153D271C76F8A6" authority="" class="Trilobita" family="Cheiruridae" genus="Sphaerexochus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phacopida" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Onukia">
<emphasis id="63A7EAD0FF906C5CFC153D271C76F8A6" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Sphaerexochus (Onukia)</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and Přibyl and Vaněk (in 
<bibRefCitation id="35424B33FF906C5CFBD23D1B1E61F8A5" author="Pribyl, A. &amp; Vanek, J. &amp; Pek, I." box="[643,843,1843,1870]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" pagination="107 - 193" refId="ref37937" refString="Pribyl, A., Vanek, J. &amp; Pek, I. (1985) Phylogeny and taxonomy of family Cheiruridae (Trilobita). Acta Universitatis Palackianae Olomucensis Facultas rerum naturalium, 83, 107 - 193." type="journal article" year="1985">
Přibyl 
<emphasis id="63A7EAD0FF906C5CFB9F3D1C1FD4F8A6" box="[718,766,1843,1869]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">et al</emphasis>
., 1985
</bibRefCitation>
) proposed two more, 
<emphasis id="63A7EAD0FF906C5CFD6F3D1B19C5F8A6" box="[1086,1263,1843,1869]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">S. (Korolevium)</emphasis>
and 
<emphasis id="63A7EAD0FF906C5CFC753D1B1DF2F89A" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">S. (Parvixochus</emphasis>
). 
<emphasis id="63A7EAD0FF906C5CF9BE3D7F1C6BF89A" box="[239,321,1879,1905]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Onukia</emphasis>
and 
<emphasis id="63A7EAD0FF906C5CF8273D7F1F28F89A" box="[374,514,1879,1905]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Parvixochus</emphasis>
are both monotypic, so do nothing to elucidate phylogenetic structure in the group. 
<emphasis id="63A7EAD0FF906C5CF9C63D531C30F87E" box="[151,282,1915,1941]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Korolevium</emphasis>
grouped a small set of Ordovician species. This was in fact retrieved as a clade in the cladistic analysis of 
<bibRefCitation id="35424B33FF906C5CF9E73DB71F0AF852" author="Congreve, C. R. &amp; Lieberman, B. S." box="[182,544,1951,1977]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" pagination="21304" refId="ref35751" refString="Congreve, C. R. &amp; Lieberman, B. S. (2011) Phylogenetic and biogeographic analysis of sphaerexochine trilobites. PLoS ONE, 6 (6), e 21304. https: // doi. org / 10.1371 / journal. pone. 0021304" type="journal article" year="2011">Congreve and Lieberman (2011</bibRefCitation>
, fig. 5), though that analysis included many species that are herein regarded as unrelated acanthoparyphines, and considered only 20 of the 50 named 
<taxonomicName id="96D34D41FF906C5CFA943DEB19E5F836" box="[965,1231,1987,2013]" class="Trilobita" family="Cheiruridae" genus="Sphaerexochus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phacopida" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis id="63A7EAD0FF906C5CFA943DEB1947F836" box="[965,1133,1987,2013]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Sphaerexochus</emphasis>
species.
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicName id="96D34D41FF906C5CFD893DEB18AAF836" authorityName="Beyrich" authorityYear="1845" box="[1240,1408,1987,2013]" class="Trilobita" family="Cheiruridae" genus="Sphaerexochus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phacopida" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="63A7EAD0FF906C5CFD893DEB18AAF836" box="[1240,1408,1987,2013]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Sphaerexochus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a difficult taxon because it has limited morphological diversity. More detailed phylogenetic analysis is required in order to understand its structure and possible bases for subdivision.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="516C36C2FF916C5DF9963AF71E93FE1E" blockId="29.[151,1437,151,501]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
The Table Cove Formation preserves a species that is the same age as the oldest known firmly assigned 
<taxonomicName id="96D34D41FF916C5DFC153AF71DDBFEF6" authorityName="Beyrich" authorityYear="1845" class="Trilobita" family="Cheiruridae" genus="Sphaerexochus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phacopida" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="63A7EAD0FF916C5DFC153AF71DDBFEF6" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Sphaerexochus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. In cephalic features, it strongly resembles 
<taxonomicName id="96D34D41FF916C5DFBB13B2B1EA2FEF6" authorityName="Beyrich" authorityYear="1845" box="[736,904,259,285]" class="Trilobita" family="Cheiruridae" genus="Sphaerexochus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phacopida" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="63A7EAD0FF916C5DFBB13B2B1EA2FEF6" box="[736,904,259,285]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Sphaerexochus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, sharing in particular what seem to be synapomorphies of the librigena (see genus discussion below). In pygidial features, it is very different, apart from having three segments. The pygidial morphology suggests potential relationships that are very different from the traditional classification of 
<taxonomicName id="96D34D41FF916C5DF8013B471CD2FE62" authorityName="Beyrich" authorityYear="1845" box="[336,504,367,393]" class="Trilobita" family="Cheiruridae" genus="Sphaerexochus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phacopida" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="63A7EAD0FF916C5DF8013B471CD2FE62" box="[336,504,367,393]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Sphaerexochus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. There are two possibilities: 1) the species represents the less derived sister species of 
<taxonomicName id="96D34D41FF916C5DF9E73BBB1C74FE46" authorityName="Beyrich" authorityYear="1845" box="[182,350,403,429]" class="Trilobita" family="Cheiruridae" genus="Sphaerexochus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phacopida" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="63A7EAD0FF916C5DF9E73BBB1C74FE46" box="[182,350,403,429]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Sphaerexochus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; or 2) the cephalic features of the species are convergent on those of 
<taxonomicName id="96D34D41FF916C5DFD343BBB1827FE46" authorityName="Beyrich" authorityYear="1845" box="[1125,1293,403,429]" class="Trilobita" family="Cheiruridae" genus="Sphaerexochus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phacopida" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="63A7EAD0FF916C5DFD343BBB1827FE46" box="[1125,1293,403,429]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Sphaerexochus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and the species is unrelated. We tentatively advance the hypothesis that the first possibility is correct and assign the new species to a monotypic new genus classified with question as 
<taxonomicName id="96D34D41FF916C5DFBA33BF31E9FFE1E" authorityName="Opik" authorityYear="1937" box="[754,949,475,501]" pageId="29" pageNumber="29" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Sphaerexochinae">Sphaerexochinae</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
